uiredAcks parameter.\n\n7. **Append Coordination (ReplicaManager.scala)**: The appendRecords method (lines 674-712) validates requiredAcks and calls appendRecordsToLeader. Critically, it then calls maybeAddDelayedProduce (line 704) with the requiredAcks parameter.\n\n8. **Write Acknowledgment Decision (ReplicaManager.scala)**: The delayedProduceRequestRequired method (lines 1355-1361) determines when the broker must wait for acknowledgments. It returns true only when requiredAcks == -1 (meaning 'all' replicas), combined with non-empty entries and at least one successful append. When true, a DelayedProduce operation is created in the purgatory to wait for in-sync replicas to acknowledge before responding.\n\n9. **Broker-Side Enforcement (Partition.scala)**: In the appendRecordsToLeader method (lines 1361-1388), when requiredAcks == -1 (line 1370), the code checks if the in-sync replica set size is sufficient to meet the min.isr requirement. If not, it throws NotEnoughReplicasException, preventing writes when insufficient replicas are in sync. This is the critical enforcement point that determines acknowledgment behavior based on the acks value.\n\nIn summary:\n- **acks=0**: Producer does not wait for broker response (no delayed produce operation created).\n- **acks=1**: Producer waits only for leader acknowledgment (no delayed produce operation).\n- **acks=-1 (or 'all')**: Producer waits for all in-sync replicas, enforced by DelayedProduce and min.isr validation, ensuring highest durability guarantees."
